Why not header versioning (`Accept: application/vnd.myapi.v2+json`)? Because you can't test it with a browser, curl commands get ugly, and every proxy/CDN config needs special handling. URL versioning is visible, cacheable, and debuggable.

That will panic on missing or malformed headers. Auth extraction needs to be defensive:

```rust
use axum::{
    extract::FromRequestParts,
    http::{request::Parts, StatusCode},
    response::IntoResponse,
};

pub struct BearerToken(pub String);

#[axum::async_trait]
impl<S: Send + Sync> FromRequestParts<S> for BearerToken {
    type Rejection = AuthError;

    async fn from_request_parts(parts: &mut Parts, _state: &S) -> Result<Self, Self::Rejection> {
        let header = parts.headers
            .get("authorization")
            .ok_or(AuthError::Missing)?
            .to_str()
            .map_err(|_| AuthError::Malformed)?;

        // Case-insensitive "Bearer " prefix per RFC 6750
        if header.len() < 7 || !header[..7].eq_ignore_ascii_case("bearer ") {
            return Err(AuthError::Malformed);
        }

        let token = header[7..].trim();
        if token.is_empty() {
            return Err(AuthError::Empty);
        }

        // Basic token format validation (no control chars, reasonable length)
        if token.len() > 4096 || token.chars().any(|c| c.is_control()) {
            return Err(AuthError::Malformed);
        }

        Ok(BearerToken(token.to_string()))
    }
}

#[derive(Debug)]
pub enum AuthError {
    Missing,
    Malformed,
    Empty,
}

impl IntoResponse for AuthError {
    fn into_response(self) -> axum::response::Response {
        let (status, message) = match self {
            AuthError::Missing => (StatusCode::UNAUTHORIZED, "missing authorization header"),
            AuthError::Malformed => (StatusCode::BAD_REQUEST, "malformed authorization header"),
            AuthError::Empty => (StatusCode::UNAUTHORIZED, "empty bearer token"),
        };
        (status, serde_json::json!({"error": {"code": "auth_error", "message": message}}).to_string()).into_response()
    }
}
```

Five things your original missed: (1) The `Authorization` header might not exist. (2) The header value might not be valid UTF-8. (3) "Bearer" comparison should be case-insensitive per RFC 6750. (4) The token after "Bearer " might be empty. (5) No length/content validation allows injection attacks.

Yes, this is a security vulnerability. Internal error details leak your schema, enabling SQL injection reconnaissance. Map internal errors to safe API errors:

```rust
use rusqlite;

#[derive(Debug)]
pub enum ServiceError {
    Conflict { resource: &'static str, field: &'static str },
    NotFound { resource: &'static str },
    Internal(anyhow::Error),
}

impl From<rusqlite::Error> for ServiceError {
    fn from(err: rusqlite::Error) -> Self {
        match &err {
            rusqlite::Error::SqliteFailure(ffi_err, Some(msg)) => {
                if ffi_err.extended_code == rusqlite::ffi::SQLITE_CONSTRAINT_UNIQUE {
                    // Don't expose which column -- the caller knows what they sent
                    ServiceError::Conflict {
                        resource: "resource",
                        field: "identifier",
                    }
                } else {
                    // Log the real error server-side
                    eprintln!("Database error: {}", msg);
                    ServiceError::Internal(err.into())
                }
            }
            _ => {
                eprintln!("Database error: {}", err);
                ServiceError::Internal(err.into())
            }
        }
    }
}

impl ServiceError {
    pub fn to_api_response(&self) -> (u16, serde_json::Value) {
        match self {
            ServiceError::Conflict { resource, field } => (
                409,
                serde_json::json!({
                    "error": {
                        "code": "conflict",
                        "message": format!("A {} with this {} already exists", resource, field),
                    }
                }),
            ),
            ServiceError::NotFound { resource } => (
                404,
                serde_json::json!({
                    "error": {
                        "code": "not_found",
                        "message": format!("{} not found", resource),
                    }
                }),
            ),
            ServiceError::Internal(_) => (
                500,
                serde_json::json!({
                    "error": {
                        "code": "internal_error",
                        "message": "An internal error occurred. Please try again.",
                    }
                }),
            ),
        }
    }
}
```

Rules: (1) Never expose SQL error messages, table names, or column names. (2) Log the full error server-side with a request ID. (3) Return a generic, consistent error structure. (4) Use specific codes like `conflict` rather than exposing the constraint name.

Here's a complete JSON-RPC 2.0 handler with batch support and proper error codes:

```rust
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};
use std::collections::HashMap;

#[derive(Debug, Deserialize)]
#[serde(untagged)]
pub enum JsonRpcIncoming {
    Single(JsonRpcMessage),
    Batch(Vec<JsonRpcMessage>),
}

#[derive(Debug, Deserialize)]
pub struct JsonRpcMessage {
    pub jsonrpc: String,
    #[serde(default)]
    pub id: Option<serde_json::Value>,
    pub method: Option<String>,
    #[serde(default)]
    pub params: serde_json::Value,
    // Response fields
    pub result: Option<serde_json::Value>,
    pub error: Option<JsonRpcErrorData>,
}

#[derive(Debug, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub struct JsonRpcErrorData {
    pub code: i32,
    pub message: String,
    #[serde(skip_serializing_if = "Option::is_none")]
    pub data: Option<serde_json::Value>,
}

// Standard JSON-RPC error codes
pub const PARSE_ERROR: i32 = -32700;
pub const INVALID_REQUEST: i32 = -32600;
pub const METHOD_NOT_FOUND: i32 = -32601;
pub const INVALID_PARAMS: i32 = -32602;
pub const INTERNAL_ERROR: i32 = -32603;

pub type HandlerFn = Box<dyn Fn(serde_json::Value) -> anyhow::Result<serde_json::Value> + Send + Sync>;

pub struct JsonRpcRouter {
    handlers: HashMap<String, HandlerFn>,
}

impl JsonRpcRouter {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self { handlers: HashMap::new() }
    }

    pub fn register(&mut self, method: &str, handler: HandlerFn) {
        self.handlers.insert(method.to_string(), handler);
    }

    pub fn handle(&self, raw: &str) -> Option<String> {
        let incoming: JsonRpcIncoming = match serde_json::from_str(raw) {
            Ok(v) => v,
            Err(_) => {
                return Some(serde_json::to_string(&self.error_response(
                    serde_json::Value::Null, PARSE_ERROR, "Parse error"
                )).unwrap());
            }
        };

        match incoming {
            JsonRpcIncoming::Single(msg) => self.handle_message(msg)
                .map(|r| serde_json::to_string(&r).unwrap()),
            JsonRpcIncoming::Batch(msgs) => {
                let results: Vec<_> = msgs.into_iter()
                    .filter_map(|m| self.handle_message(m))
                    .collect();
                if results.is_empty() { None }
                else { Some(serde_json::to_string(&results).unwrap()) }
            }
        }
    }

    fn handle_message(&self, msg: JsonRpcMessage) -> Option<serde_json::Value> {
        // Notifications (no id) get no response
        let id = msg.id?;
        let method = match msg.method {
            Some(m) => m,
            None => return Some(self.error_response(id, INVALID_REQUEST, "Missing method")),
        };

        let handler = match self.handlers.get(&method) {
            Some(h) => h,
            None => return Some(self.error_response(id, METHOD_NOT_FOUND,
                &format!("Method not found: {}", method))),
        };

        match handler(msg.params) {
            Ok(result) => Some(serde_json::json!({
                "jsonrpc": "2.0", "id": id, "result": result
            })),
            Err(e) => Some(self.error_response(id, INTERNAL_ERROR, &e.to_string())),
        }
    }

    fn error_response(&self, id: serde_json::Value, code: i32, message: &str) -> serde_json::Value {
        serde_json::json!({
            "jsonrpc": "2.0",
            "id": id,
            "error": { "code": code, "message": message }
        })
    }
}
```

Critical detail: notifications (requests without an `id`) must not produce a response -- that's why `handle_message` returns `Option`. Sending a response to a notification violates the spec.

Here's an MCP server implementing `tools/list` and `tools/call`:

```rust
use serde_json::{json, Value};
use anyhow::{Context, Result};

pub struct McpToolServer {
    project_root: std::path::PathBuf,
}

impl McpToolServer {
    pub fn new(project_root: impl Into<std::path::PathBuf>) -> Self {
        Self { project_root: project_root.into() }
    }

    pub fn handle_method(&self, method: &str, params: Value) -> Result<Value> {
        match method {
            "initialize" => Ok(json!({
                "protocolVersion": "2024-11-05",
                "capabilities": {
                    "tools": { "listChanged": false }
                },
                "serverInfo": {
                    "name": "forge-tools",
                    "version": env!("CARGO_PKG_VERSION")
                }
            })),
            "tools/list" => self.list_tools(),
            "tools/call" => self.call_tool(params),
            _ => anyhow::bail!("unknown method: {}", method),
        }
    }

    fn list_tools(&self) -> Result<Value> {
        Ok(json!({
            "tools": [
                {
                    "name": "file_read",
                    "description": "Read a file's contents",
                    "inputSchema": {
                        "type": "object",
                        "required": ["path"],
                        "properties": {
                            "path": { "type": "string", "description": "File path relative to project root" }
                        }
                    }
                },
                {
                    "name": "file_write",
                    "description": "Write content to a file",
                    "inputSchema": {
                        "type": "object",
                        "required": ["path", "content"],
                        "properties": {
                            "path": { "type": "string" },
                            "content": { "type": "string" }
                        }
                    }
                }
            ]
        }))
    }

    fn call_tool(&self, params: Value) -> Result<Value> {
        let name = params["name"].as_str().context("missing tool name")?;
        let args = &params["arguments"];

        match name {
            "file_read" => {
                let path = args["path"].as_str().context("missing path")?;
                let full_path = self.resolve_safe_path(path)?;
                let content = std::fs::read_to_string(&full_path)
                    .with_context(|| format!("failed to read {}", full_path.display()))?;
                Ok(json!({
                    "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": content }]
                }))
            }
            "file_write" => {
                let path = args["path"].as_str().context("missing path")?;
                let content = args["content"].as_str().context("missing content")?;
                let full_path = self.resolve_safe_path(path)?;
                if let Some(parent) = full_path.parent() {
                    std::fs::create_dir_all(parent)?;
                }
                std::fs::write(&full_path, content)?;
                Ok(json!({
                    "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": format!("Wrote {} bytes to {}", content.len(), path) }]
                }))
            }
            _ => Ok(json!({
                "content": [{ "type": "text", "text": format!("Unknown tool: {}", name) }],
                "isError": true
            })),
        }
    }

    /// Resolve path and ensure it stays within project root (path traversal prevention).
    fn resolve_safe_path(&self, path: &str) -> Result<std::path::PathBuf> {
        let candidate = self.project_root.join(path);
        let canonical = candidate.canonicalize()
            .with_context(|| format!("path does not exist: {}", path))?;
        if !canonical.starts_with(&self.project_root) {
            anyhow::bail!("path traversal blocked: {} escapes project root", path);
        }
        Ok(canonical)
    }
}
```

Security: the `resolve_safe_path` method prevents `../../etc/passwd` attacks by canonicalizing and checking the path stays under the project root. This is P0 security for any tool server.

The SSE spec (W3C EventSource) has subtle rules most implementations miss. Here's a spec-compliant parser:

```rust
/// SSE parser following https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/server-sent-events.html
pub struct SpecCompliantSseParser {
    buffer: String,
    event_type: String,
    data_buffer: String,
    last_event_id: String,
    retry_ms: Option<u64>,
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct SseEvent {
    pub event_type: String,
    pub data: String,
    pub last_event_id: String,
}

impl SpecCompliantSseParser {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self {
            buffer: String::new(),
            event_type: String::new(),
            data_buffer: String::new(),
            last_event_id: String::new(),
            retry_ms: None,
        }
    }

    pub fn feed(&mut self, chunk: &str) -> Vec<SseEvent> {
        self.buffer.push_str(chunk);
        let mut events = Vec::new();

        loop {
            // Spec: lines end with CR, LF, or CRLF
            let line_end = self.buffer.find(|c| c == '\n' || c == '\r');
            let Some(pos) = line_end else { break };

            let line = self.buffer[..pos].to_string();

            // Handle CRLF: consume both characters
            let skip = if self.buffer.as_bytes().get(pos) == Some(&b'\r')
                && self.buffer.as_bytes().get(pos + 1) == Some(&b'\n') {
                pos + 2
            } else {
                pos + 1
            };
            self.buffer = self.buffer[skip..].to_string();

            if line.is_empty() {
                // Dispatch event
                if !self.data_buffer.is_empty() {
                    // Spec: remove trailing LF from data
                    if self.data_buffer.ends_with('\n') {
                        self.data_buffer.pop();
                    }
                    events.push(SseEvent {
                        event_type: if self.event_type.is_empty() {
                            "message".to_string() // Spec: default event type
                        } else {
                            std::mem::take(&mut self.event_type)
                        },
                        data: std::mem::take(&mut self.data_buffer),
                        last_event_id: self.last_event_id.clone(),
                    });
                }
                self.event_type.clear();
                continue;
            }

            // Spec: lines starting with U+003A COLON are comments
            if line.starts_with(':') { continue; }

            let (field, value) = if let Some(colon_pos) = line.find(':') {
                let f = &line[..colon_pos];
                let mut v = &line[colon_pos + 1..];
                // Spec: if first char after colon is space, remove it
                if v.starts_with(' ') { v = &v[1..]; }
                (f.to_string(), v.to_string())
            } else {
                (line, String::new())
            };

            match field.as_str() {
                "event" => self.event_type = value,
                "data" => {
                    self.data_buffer.push_str(&value);
                    self.data_buffer.push('\n'); // Spec: append LF after each data line
                }
                "id" => {
                    // Spec: if value contains U+0000 NULL, ignore the field
                    if !value.contains('\0') {
                        self.last_event_id = value;
                    }
                }
                "retry" => {
                    if let Ok(ms) = value.parse::<u64>() {
                        self.retry_ms = Some(ms);
                    }
                    // Spec: if not a valid integer, ignore
                }
                _ => {} // Spec: ignore unknown fields
            }
        }

        events
    }
}
```

Three things most SSE parsers get wrong: (1) The default event type is "message", not empty string. (2) Data lines accumulate with newlines between them -- multi-line data fields are common. (3) The `id` field must reject values containing null bytes (this prevents injection attacks on the `Last-Event-ID` header during reconnection).

Here's a typed WebSocket protocol with message correlation and error handling:

```rust
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};
use uuid::Uuid;

/// All messages over the WebSocket connection follow this envelope.
#[derive(Debug, Serialize, Deserialize)]
#[serde(tag = "type")]
pub enum WsMessage {
    /// Client -> Server: request a tool execution
    #[serde(rename = "tool_request")]
    ToolRequest {
        id: String,
        tool: String,
        arguments: serde_json::Value,
    },
    /// Server -> Client: tool execution result
    #[serde(rename = "tool_result")]
    ToolResult {
        id: String,
        success: bool,
        content: String,
        #[serde(skip_serializing_if = "Option::is_none")]
        error: Option<String>,
    },
    /// Server -> Client: streaming token from inference
    #[serde(rename = "token")]
    Token {
        text: String,
        is_final: bool,
    },
    /// Bidirectional: ping/pong for keepalive
    #[serde(rename = "ping")]
    Ping { timestamp: u64 },
    #[serde(rename = "pong")]
    Pong { timestamp: u64 },
    /// Server -> Client: error that isn't tied to a specific request
    #[serde(rename = "error")]
    Error {
        code: String,
        message: String,
    },
}

impl WsMessage {
    pub fn tool_request(tool: &str, arguments: serde_json::Value) -> Self {
        WsMessage::ToolRequest {
            id: Uuid::new_v4().to_string(),
            tool: tool.to_string(),
            arguments,
        }
    }

    pub fn success_result(id: &str, content: String) -> Self {
        WsMessage::ToolResult {
            id: id.to_string(),
            success: true,
            content,
            error: None,
        }
    }

    pub fn error_result(id: &str, error: String) -> Self {
        WsMessage::ToolResult {
            id: id.to_string(),
            success: false,
            content: String::new(),
            error: Some(error),
        }
    }
}

/// Serialize a WsMessage to a WebSocket text frame.
pub fn encode(msg: &WsMessage) -> Result<String, serde_json::Error> {
    serde_json::to_string(msg)
}

/// Deserialize from a WebSocket text frame.
pub fn decode(text: &str) -> Result<WsMessage, serde_json::Error> {
    serde_json::from_str(text)
}
```

Using `#[serde(tag = "type")]` gives you internally-tagged JSON: `{"type": "tool_request", "id": "...", ...}`. This makes the protocol self-describing and easy to debug with browser DevTools. The `id` field on tool requests/results enables correlation -- essential when multiple tools execute concurrently.

Use content negotiation with the `Accept` header. The same endpoint serves both modes:

```rust
use axum::{
    extract::{Json, State},
    http::HeaderMap,
    response::{IntoResponse, Response, sse::{Event, Sse}},
};
use futures_util::stream::Stream;

async fn completions(
    headers: HeaderMap,
    State(engine): State<InferenceEngine>,
    Json(req): Json<CompletionRequest>,
) -> Response {
    let wants_stream = req.stream.unwrap_or(false)
        || headers.get("accept")
            .and_then(|v| v.to_str().ok())
            .map(|v| v.contains("text/event-stream"))
            .unwrap_or(false);

    if wants_stream {
        stream_response(engine, req).await.into_response()
    } else {
        sync_response(engine, req).await.into_response()
    }
}

async fn sync_response(
    engine: InferenceEngine,
    req: CompletionRequest,
) -> impl IntoResponse {
    match engine.generate(&req.prompt, req.max_tokens.unwrap_or(256)).await {
        Ok(result) => Json(serde_json::json!({
            "choices": [{"text": result.text, "finish_reason": "stop"}],
            "usage": {
                "prompt_tokens": result.prompt_tokens,
                "completion_tokens": result.completion_tokens,
            }
        })).into_response(),
        Err(e) => (
            axum::http::StatusCode::INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR,
            Json(serde_json::json!({"error": {"message": e.to_string()}})),
        ).into_response(),
    }
}

async fn stream_response(
    engine: InferenceEngine,
    req: CompletionRequest,
) -> Sse<impl Stream<Item = Result<Event, std::convert::Infallible>>> {
    let (tx, mut rx) = tokio::sync::mpsc::channel(128);

    tokio::spawn(async move {
        if let Err(e) = engine.generate_stream(
            &req.prompt,
            req.max_tokens.unwrap_or(256),
            tx,
        ).await {
            eprintln!("Stream error: {}", e);
        }
    });

    let stream = async_stream::stream! {
        while let Some(token) = rx.recv().await {
            let data = serde_json::json!({
                "choices": [{"delta": {"content": token.text}}]
            });
            yield Ok(Event::default().data(data.to_string()));
        }
        yield Ok(Event::default().data("[DONE]"));
    };

    Sse::new(stream)
}
```

HTTP/2 multiplexing means the streaming response shares the connection with other requests. No special server config needed -- axum with `hyper` serves HTTP/2 automatically when the client negotiates it via ALPN.

Use the `keyring` crate for a unified API, but understand the platform differences:

```rust
use anyhow::{Context, Result};

const SERVICE_NAME: &str = "com.folktech.forge";

pub struct SecureCredentialStore;

impl SecureCredentialStore {
    /// Store a credential securely in the OS keychain.
    pub fn store(key: &str, value: &str) -> Result<()> {
        let entry = keyring::Entry::new(SERVICE_NAME, key)
            .context("failed to create keyring entry")?;
        entry.set_password(value)
            .context("failed to store credential")?;
        Ok(())
    }

    /// Retrieve a credential from the OS keychain.
    pub fn retrieve(key: &str) -> Result<Option<String>> {
        let entry = keyring::Entry::new(SERVICE_NAME, key)
            .context("failed to create keyring entry")?;
        match entry.get_password() {
            Ok(value) => Ok(Some(value)),
            Err(keyring::Error::NoEntry) => Ok(None),
            Err(keyring::Error::PlatformFailure(e)) => {
                // On macOS: user denied Keychain access
                // On Windows: Credential Manager unavailable
                eprintln!("Keychain access denied: {}. Falling back to env var.", e);
                Ok(std::env::var(key).ok())
            }
            Err(e) => Err(e).context("keyring error"),
        }
    }

    /// Resolve an API key with fallback chain:
    /// 1. OS keychain
    /// 2. Environment variable
    /// 3. Config file (plaintext, warn user)
    pub fn resolve_api_key(provider: &str) -> Result<Option<String>> {
        let key_name = format!("{}_API_KEY", provider.to_uppercase());

        // Try keychain first
        if let Some(value) = Self::retrieve(&key_name)? {
            return Ok(Some(value));
        }

        // Fall back to env var
        if let Ok(value) = std::env::var(&key_name) {
            // Opportunistically store in keychain for next time
            if let Err(e) = Self::store(&key_name, &value) {
                eprintln!("Note: couldn't cache key in keychain: {}", e);
            }
            return Ok(Some(value));
        }

        Ok(None)
    }
}
```

Platform gotchas: (1) macOS Keychain prompts the user for permission on first access from a new binary -- this blocks the thread, so call from a context where blocking is acceptable. (2) Windows Credential Manager has a 2560-byte limit per credential. (3) On Linux, `keyring` uses `libsecret` (GNOME Keyring) which requires a running D-Bus session -- headless servers won't have this. For Linux, fall back to encrypted file storage.

Use `dirs` crate for standard locations and normalize all paths through a config layer:

```rust
use std::path::PathBuf;
use anyhow::{Context, Result};

pub struct AppPaths {
    pub config_dir: PathBuf,   // User-editable config
    pub cache_dir: PathBuf,    // Deletable cache (API responses, model downloads)
    pub data_dir: PathBuf,     // Persistent data (sessions, facts, evolution DB)
}

impl AppPaths {
    pub fn detect() -> Result<Self> {
        // macOS: ~/Library/Application Support/forge
        // Windows: C:\Users\<user>\AppData\Roaming\forge
        // Linux: ~/.config/forge
        let config_dir = dirs::config_dir()
            .context("cannot determine config directory")?
            .join("forge");

        // macOS: ~/Library/Caches/forge
        // Windows: C:\Users\<user>\AppData\Local\forge\cache
        // Linux: ~/.cache/forge
        let cache_dir = dirs::cache_dir()
            .context("cannot determine cache directory")?
            .join("forge");

        // macOS: ~/Library/Application Support/forge (same as config on macOS)
        // Windows: C:\Users\<user>\AppData\Roaming\forge
        // Linux: ~/.local/share/forge
        let data_dir = dirs::data_dir()
            .context("cannot determine data directory")?
            .join("forge");

        // Create directories if they don't exist
        for dir in [&config_dir, &cache_dir, &data_dir] {
            std::fs::create_dir_all(dir)
                .with_context(|| format!("failed to create {}", dir.display()))?;
        }

        Ok(Self { config_dir, cache_dir, data_dir })
    }

    /// Cache directory for API response caching.
    pub fn api_cache_dir(&self) -> PathBuf {
        self.cache_dir.join("api-responses")
    }

    /// Database directory (SQLite files).
    pub fn db_path(&self, name: &str) -> PathBuf {
        self.data_dir.join(format!("{}.db", name))
    }
}
```

Never hardcode `~/.forge` -- that only works on Unix. Never use `std::env::home_dir()` (deprecated). The `dirs` crate handles the XDG spec on Linux, `NSSearchPathForDirectoriesInDomains` on macOS, and `SHGetKnownFolderPath` on Windows.

Each platform has its own certificate store. Use `reqwest` with `native-tls` or `rustls` depending on your needs:

```rust
use anyhow::{Context, Result};
use reqwest::Client;

pub fn build_platform_client() -> Result<Client> {
    let mut builder = Client::builder()
        .connect_timeout(std::time::Duration::from_secs(10))
        .timeout(std::time::Duration::from_secs(60));

    // Use native TLS on each platform:
    // macOS: Security.framework (trusts Keychain certificates)
    // Windows: SChannel (trusts Windows certificate store)
    // Linux: OpenSSL (trusts /etc/ssl/certs or distro-specific paths)
    //
    // reqwest with default features uses native-tls, which does this automatically.

    // For self-signed certs (e.g., local model server):
    if let Ok(cert_path) = std::env::var("FORGE_CA_CERT") {
        let cert_pem = std::fs::read(&cert_path)
            .with_context(|| format!("failed to read CA cert: {}", cert_path))?;
        let cert = reqwest::Certificate::from_pem(&cert_pem)
            .context("failed to parse CA certificate")?;
        builder = builder.add_root_certificate(cert);
    }

    // For local development only -- never in production
    if std::env::var("FORGE_INSECURE").is_ok() {
        eprintln!("WARNING: TLS verification disabled. Do not use in production.");
        builder = builder.danger_accept_invalid_certs(true);
    }

    builder.build().context("failed to build HTTP client")
}

/// Platform-specific CA bundle detection for manual TLS configs
pub fn system_ca_path() -> Option<std::path::PathBuf> {
    if cfg!(target_os = "macos") {
        // macOS uses Security.framework, not file paths
        None
    } else if cfg!(target_os = "windows") {
        // Windows uses SChannel, not file paths
        None
    } else {
        // Linux: check common locations
        let paths = [
            "/etc/ssl/certs/ca-certificates.crt",  // Debian/Ubuntu
            "/etc/pki/tls/certs/ca-bundle.crt",    // RHEL/CentOS
            "/etc/ssl/ca-bundle.pem",               // OpenSUSE
            "/etc/ssl/cert.pem",                     // Alpine
        ];
        paths.iter()
            .map(std::path::PathBuf::from)
            .find(|p| p.exists())
    }
}
```

In practice, `reqwest` with `native-tls` handles 99% of cases. The custom CA cert path is for corporate environments with internal PKI. The insecure mode is for local development with self-signed certs on local inference servers.

Abstract the shell behind a platform detection layer:

```rust
use anyhow::{Context, Result};
use std::path::PathBuf;
use std::process::Stdio;
use tokio::process::Command;

/// Returns (shell_binary, args_prefix) for the current platform.
pub fn shell_command() -> (&'static str, &'static [&'static str]) {
    if cfg!(windows) {
        ("cmd.exe", &["/C"])
    } else {
        ("bash", &["-c"])
    }
}

/// Returns true if the path is absolute on the current platform.
pub fn is_absolute_path(path: &str) -> bool {
    if path.starts_with('/') { return true; }
    // Windows: C:\ or D:/
    if cfg!(windows) && path.len() >= 3 {
        let bytes = path.as_bytes();
        if bytes[0].is_ascii_alphabetic() && bytes[1] == b':'
            && (bytes[2] == b'\\' || bytes[2] == b'/') {
            return true;
        }
    }
    false
}

pub async fn execute_command(
    command: &str,
    working_dir: Option<&PathBuf>,
    timeout_secs: u64,
) -> Result<CommandOutput> {
    let (shell, prefix) = shell_command();
    let mut cmd = Command::new(shell);
    for arg in prefix {
        cmd.arg(arg);
    }
    cmd.arg(command);

    if let Some(dir) = working_dir {
        cmd.current_dir(dir);
    }

    cmd.stdout(Stdio::piped())
       .stderr(Stdio::piped());

    // Platform-specific: prevent child from inheriting terminal on Unix
    #[cfg(unix)]
    {
        use std::os::unix::process::CommandExt;
        cmd.process_group(0); // New process group for clean kill
    }

    let child = cmd.spawn().context("failed to spawn shell")?;
    let output = tokio::time::timeout(
        std::time::Duration::from_secs(timeout_secs),
        child.wait_with_output(),
    ).await
        .map_err(|_| anyhow::anyhow!("command timed out after {}s", timeout_secs))?
        .context("command execution failed")?;

    Ok(CommandOutput {
        stdout: String::from_utf8_lossy(&output.stdout).to_string(),
        stderr: String::from_utf8_lossy(&output.stderr).to_string(),
        exit_code: output.status.code().unwrap_or(-1),
    })
}

pub struct CommandOutput {
    pub stdout: String,
    pub stderr: String,
    pub exit_code: i32,
}
```

Critical cross-platform detail: `process_group(0)` on Unix puts the child in its own process group so `kill` doesn't also kill the parent. On Windows, `CREATE_NEW_PROCESS_GROUP` is the equivalent -- tokio handles this internally. Without this, timeout-based kills can take down your entire application.

On macOS use `NWPathMonitor` via FFI or a simplified polling approach. On Linux, monitor network interfaces directly:

```rust
use anyhow::Result;
use std::sync::Arc;
use tokio::sync::watch;

pub struct NetworkMonitor {
    is_online: watch::Receiver<bool>,
    _handle: tokio::task::JoinHandle<()>,
}

impl NetworkMonitor {
    pub fn start() -> Self {
        let (tx, rx) = watch::channel(true); // Assume online initially

        let handle = tokio::spawn(async move {
            loop {
                let online = check_connectivity().await;
                let _ = tx.send(online);
                tokio::time::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_secs(15)).await;
            }
        });

        Self { is_online: rx, _handle: handle }
    }

    pub fn is_online(&self) -> bool {
        *self.is_online.borrow()
    }

    /// Wait until the network comes back online.
    pub async fn wait_for_connectivity(&mut self) {
        while !*self.is_online.borrow_and_update() {
            if self.is_online.changed().await.is_err() {
                break;
            }
        }
    }
}

async fn check_connectivity() -> bool {
    // Simple: try to connect to a known endpoint
    let client = reqwest::Client::builder()
        .connect_timeout(std::time::Duration::from_secs(5))
        .build()
        .unwrap();

    // Use a lightweight endpoint -- HEAD request, no body
    client.head("https://api.anthropic.com")
        .send()
        .await
        .is_ok()
}

